Summary: Subsidies boost consumer and producer surplus, but create a net government cost requiring careful economic analysis.

Blog Title: Tax incidence: distribution of the burden of a tax between consumers and producers
Summary: Tax burden distribution between buyers and sellers; depends on price elasticity of supply and demand.

Blog Title: Price floor: minimum legal price above equilibrium that creates surplus and reduces total surplus
Summary: Legal minimum price above market equilibrium reduces efficiency by creating surplus and lowering total welfare.

Blog Title: Price ceiling: maximum legal price below equilibrium that creates shortage and reduces total surplus
Summary: Price ceilings set below equilibrium cause shortages, reduce total surplus, and create market inefficiencies.

Blog Title: Competitive market: market structure where demand and supply determine price and maximise total surplus
Summary: Price set by supply and demand maximizes total surplus for society in a competitive market.

Blog Title: Deadweight loss: loss of total surplus caused by market distortion such as taxes or price controls
Summary: Taxes or price controls can cause deadweight loss, reducing total surplus in markets.

Blog Title: Market efficiency: situation where total surplus is maximised
Summary: Market surplus peaks when efficiency is achieved, maximizing combined benefits for buyers and sellers.

Blog Title: Economic welfare: total benefit to society from the production and consumption of goods and services
Summary: Net benefits to society from goods and services production/consumption.

Blog Title: Total surplus: sum of consumer surplus and producer surplus
Summary: Surplus total = consumer surplus + producer surplus. It measures the net benefit to society from a market transaction, representing economic efficiency.

Blog Title: Producer surplus: difference between the price producers receive and the minimum they are willing to accept
Summary: Producer surplus: difference between price received and the minimum sellers would accept. It measures seller net benefit in a market transaction.

Blog Title: Consumer surplus: difference between what consumers are willing to pay and what they actually pay
Summary: Value minus price: how market transactions benefit buyers through surplus.

Blog Title: Composite demand: a good demanded for multiple different uses
Summary: Multi-use goods create price linkages across markets. Composite demand analysis shows how supply shifts in one use affect all others.

Blog Title: Competitive demand: demand for goods that are substitutes
Summary: Demand for substitutes: a competitive analysis of price, preference, and market share dynamics.

Blog Title: Stationary point: A sort of graph where it stops increasing or decreasing
Summary: Stationary points are where a function's derivative equals zero, indicating potential local maxima, minima, or inflection points.

Blog Title: The slant height is the diagonal distance from an apex down a lateral surface
Summary: In a cone, the slant height is the shortest distance from a point on the circumference of the base to the spot.

Blog Title: Sine rule: In any triangle, the ratio of the sine of an angle to the length of the side opposite the angle is always the same
Summary: The sine rule relates triangle sides to their opposite angles. It solves for unknowns in non-right triangles.

Blog Title: The sine ratio, fundamental in trigonometry
Summary: Compares the length of a triangle's opposite side to its hypotenuse for a given angle.

Blog Title: Simplest form: Simplifying an expression or fraction by eliminating common factors
Summary: A equivalent fraction where the numerator and denominator are themselves allowable whole numbers. Also called lowest term.

Blog Title: Simple interest: Interest that is calculated only on the original amount borrowed or invested
Summary: Simple interest is a fixed percentage of principal, calculated linearly over time for loans or investments. It is foundational.

Blog Title: Similar: Plane objects that have the same shape and proportion but are different in size
Summary: Two plane shapes are similar if they share identical angles and proportional corresponding sides, differing only in scale.

Blog Title: Joint supply: when two goods are produced together
Summary: Two goods from one process: joint supply explained.

Blog Title: Joint demand: when two goods are consumed together
Summary: Two goods consumed together. Interlinked demand patterns affect pricing and market dynamics for complementary products.

Blog Title: New equilibrium: the new price and quantity after a shift of demand or supply
Summary: New equilibrium defines the adjusted market price and quantity established after a shift in demand or supply forces.

Blog Title: Set builder notation: A way of describing what elements are in a set without having to list them all
Summary: Set builder notation describes a set by specifying the properties its members must satisfy, concisely defining collections in mathematics.

Blog Title: Set: A list or collection of objects that share a characteristic
Summary: 135 is an odd composite integer, uniquely expressible as 1¹ + 3² + 5³. A digitally self-descriptive Harshad number.

Blog Title: Selling price: The price that a trader sells goods for
Summary: Selling price is the sum of cost and profit, fundamental to revenue and profit margin mathematics.

Blog Title: Supply shift: movement of the entire supply curve due to non-price factors
Summary: Supply shifts move entire curves from factors like tech or costs, changing quantities supplied at every price point.

Blog Title: Demand shift: movement of the entire demand curve due to non-price factors
Summary: Demand shifts move curves due to non-price factors like trends, income, or tastes. This changes quantities sought at all price points.

Blog Title: Signalling function of price: price signals information to market participants about scarcity and demand
Summary: Prices signal scarcity and demand, coordinating market actions.

Blog Title: Incentive function of price: ability of price changes to motivate producers and consumers
Summary: Price signals shift production and consumption, balancing markets via producer profits and consumer savings.

Blog Title: Rationing function of price: ability of price to limit demand when supply is scarce
Summary: Prices curb demand when supplies dwindle, allocating scarce goods efficiently in free markets.

Blog Title: Excess supply (surplus): quantity supplied exceeds quantity demanded at a price above equilibrium
Summary: Excess supply occurs when price exceeds equilibrium, leading to unsold goods as quantity supplied outstrips quantity demanded.

Blog Title: Excess demand (shortage): quantity demanded exceeds quantity supplied at a price below equilibrium
Summary: At below-equilibrium prices, quantity demanded exceeds quantity supplied, creating market shortages.

Blog Title: Scale: A ratio that indicates how much smaller (or larger) a drawing is from the original object
Summary: Scale defines proportional relationships, crucial for maps, models, and geometry. It uses ratios to shrink or enlarge objects while preserving their relative shapes.

Blog Title: Equilibrium quantity: quantity bought and sold at the equilibrium price
Summary: Market balance point: the precise amount of goods exchanged at the established equilibrium price where supply meets demand.

Blog Title: Equilibrium price: price where demand and supply are balanced
Summary: Price equilibrium: where market demand meets supply, achieving balance.

Blog Title: Shift in supply: movement of the whole supply curve caused by non-price factors
Summary: Supply shifts curve; price stays same, factors like tech or costs change quantity supplied at every price.

Blog Title: Contraction of supply: decrease in quantity supplied due to a fall in price
Summary: Supply decrease from lower price: quantity falls as price drops.

Blog Title: Scalar: A quantity that has size (magnitude) but not direction
Summary: A scalar is a mathematical quantity defined solely by magnitude, lacking directional properties, fundamental to algebra and physics.

Blog Title: Sample space diagram: A list of diagram that shows all the equally likely outcomes of an ‘experiment’
Summary: Sample space diagrams visually map all possible outcomes of a probability experiment, organizing results for clear analysis.

Blog Title: Sample space: All the possible outcomes of an event or combination of events
Summary: Sample space: the foundational set of all possible outcomes in a probability experiment, defining the realm of random events.

Blog Title: Relative frequency: The experimental probability of an event happening
Summary: Relative frequency measures event occurrence in trials. It estimates probability, stabilizing with more data—a core concept in statistics and data analysis.

Blog Title: Region: A region in a plane that satisfies a set of linear inequalities
Summary: A mathematical region is a defined, continuous subset of a space, such as the area within a shape on a plane or a volume in 3D space.

Blog Title: Rationalising the denominator: Expressing the denominator of any fraction as a rational number by removing any surds
Summary: Rationalising the denominator eliminates radicals from a fraction's base, creating a simpler, standardised form for exact calculation.

Blog Title: Inverse function: A function that does the opposite of the original function
Summary: Inverse functions reverse another function's mapping, swapping domain and range under specific conditions.

Blog Title: Extension of supply: increase in quantity supplied due to a rise in price
Summary: Price rise triggers more quantity supplied. Basic market response to higher prices.

Blog Title: Supply curve: graphical representation showing the relationship between price and quantity supplied
Summary: Price up, quantity up. Supply curve: A positive price-quantity relationship.

Blog Title: Law of supply: direct relationship between price and quantity supplied
Summary: Price up, supply up. Direct relationship defines market production incentives.

Blog Title: Supply: quantity of a good producers are willing and able to sell at different prices
Summary: Producers' supply quantity at various prices, showing market response.

Blog Title: Intersection: The intersection of two sets is the set of elements that are found in both sets
Summary: Intersection identifies shared elements between sets, forming the core foundation for Venn diagrams and logical analysis in mathematics.

Blog Title: Complementary goods: goods that are consumed together
Summary: Study of complementary goods: how paired consumption shapes market pricing, demand elasticity, and cross-industry business strategies.

Blog Title: Substitute goods: goods that can replace each other in consumption
Summary: Substitutes serve similar needs. When price rises for one, demand increases for the other, illustrating key market interdependence and consumer choice.

Blog Title: Inferior good: good for which demand decreases as income increases
Summary: Demand for inferior goods falls as consumer income rises, often replaced by premium alternatives.

Blog Title: Interquartile range: The difference between the upper and lower quartiles
Summary: Interquartile range (IQR) measures statistical dispersion. It is the middle 50% of data, calculated as Q3 minus Q1, mitigating outlier influence.

Blog Title: Interest rate: The percentage charged for borrowing, or earned for investing, money
Summary: Interest rate mathematically models growth or cost over time. It’s a percentage used in formulas for compound interest, determining future value from a present principal amount.

Blog Title: Normal good: good for which demand increases as income increases
Summary: Demand rises with income. Normal goods reflect consumer prosperity and purchasing power growth.

Blog Title: Interest: The amount charged for borrowing, or earned for investing, money
Summary: Interest is the cost of borrowed money or reward for invested capital. It is calculated mathematically as a percentage of the principal amount over a specific period.

Blog Title: Shift in demand: movement of the whole demand curve caused by non-price factors
Summary: Demand shifts move the entire curve due to non-price factors like income, tastes, or expectations, altering quantities demanded at every price.

Blog Title: Contraction of demand: decrease in quantity demanded due to a rise in price
Summary: Demand contracts when prices rise. This abstract explores the inverse relationship's mechanisms and market impacts.

Blog Title: Extension of demand: increase in quantity demanded due to a fall in price
Summary: Extension of demand: when lower prices lead consumers to buy more of a good, moving along its demand curve. A core microeconomic concept.

Blog Title: Demand curve: graphical representation showing the relationship between price and quantity demanded
Summary: Graph showing how price changes affect the quantity of a good or service buyers want to purchase.

Blog Title: Index notation: A method of writing number using a base number and a power
Summary: Notation using superscripts and subscripts to concisely represent elements, operations, and sequences in mathematics.

Blog Title: Law of demand: inverse relationship between price and quantity demanded
Summary: Demand law: price increases cause quantity demanded to fall, and vice versa.

Blog Title: Demand: quantity of a good consumers are willing and able to buy at different prices
Summary: Consumers' quantity demanded across price points: the core law of demand.

Blog Title: Specialisation of resources: concept that some resources are better suited to producing certain goods than others
Summary: Efficient resource allocation by matching specialized assets to their most productive uses, boosting output & economic welfare.

Blog Title: Increasing opportunity cost: situation where the PPC is concave (bowed outward) because resources are not equally efficient in producing both goods
Summary: PPC bowed outward—increasing opportunity cost. Resources are not equally efficient in producing both goods.

Blog Title: Hyperbola (Also called reciprocal graphs)
Summary: The hyperbola, a conic section formed by a plane intersecting two cones, features two distinct, mirrored curves with reciprocal properties.

Blog Title: Constant opportunity cost: situation where the PPC is a straight line
Summary: Vital tools for progress, capital goods drive economic growth and power innovation across all industries.

Blog Title: Histogram: A specialized graph used to illustrate grouped continuous data
Summary: A bar graph displaying the frequency distribution of continuous numerical data in specified intervals.

Blog Title: Function notation: An alternative mathematical way of writing equations
Summary: Function notation, like f(x), names rules linking inputs to outputs, enabling precise mathematical analysis and modeling of relationships between variables.

Blog Title: Frequency density: The frequency of a class divided by the width of the class
Summary: Frequency density is the concentration of observations within a class interval, calculated by dividing frequency by class width for accurate histogram representation.

Blog Title: Factorisation: To rewrite an expression using brackets
Summary: Factorization breaks numbers into multiplicative components, fundamental to algebra, cryptography, and simplifying expressions.

Blog Title: Consumer goods: goods used to satisfy immediate wants of households
Summary: Machinery and equipment enabling production, capital goods are foundational to economic growth and innovation across industries.

Blog Title:  Capital goods: goods used to produce other goods and services (machinery, equipment)
Summary: Machinery and equipment enabling production, capital goods are foundational to economic growth and innovation across industries.

Blog Title: Economic growth: increase in the productive capacity of an economy shown by an outward shift of the PPC
Summary: Economic growth expands an economy's output potential, represented by an outward shift of its Production Possibilities Curve (PPC).

Blog Title: Underutilisation: resources not fully used, shown by a point inside the PPC
Summary: Resources underused: point inside PPC. Output below max capacity.

Blog Title: Full employment of resources: all available resources are used in production with no unemployment of factors
Summary: Full employment uses all economic resources, leaving no factors idle. It optimizes production.

Blog Title: Allocative efficiency: producing the combination of goods most desired by society
Summary: Maximizing output from given resources, driving economic growth through optimal production efficiency.

Blog Title: Extrapolation: A value determined by continuing a line of best fit beyond the plotted data
Summary: Extrapolation estimates values beyond a known data range, extending trends to predict or infer unknown points.

Blog Title: Productive efficiency: producing the maximum possible output from available resources
Summary: Maximizing output from given resources, driving economic growth through optimal production efficiency.

Blog Title: Exponential: A function formed when the variable is in the index
Summary: The exponential function describes explosive growth or decay, where a constant base is raised to a variable power, fundamental to modeling natural phenomena.

Blog Title: An exponent denotes repeated multiplication
Summary: Another word for power or index, indicating how many times a base number is multiplied by itself.

Blog Title: Exact value: Precise or accurate value, not an approximation
Summary: An unequivocal, fixed mathematical quantity, not an approximation. Essential for proofs, definitions, and precision in all calculations.

Blog Title: Production possibility curve (PPC): curve showing the maximum possible combinations of two goods an economy can produce with given resources
Summary: Max output combos of two goods: given resources & tech. Scarcity, trade-offs, efficiency.

Blog Title:  Inequality: uneven distribution of income and wealth in society
Summary: Wealth concentration: trends, consequences, and policy solutions for societal inequality.

Blog Title: Externalities: costs or benefits of economic activity affecting third parties
Summary: Third-party costs and benefits from economic activity, often unaccounted for.

Blog Title: Demerit goods: goods that are considered harmful and over-consumed in a free market
Summary: Harmful goods over-consumed in free markets, requiring intervention to reduce social costs.

Blog Title: Merit goods: goods that are considered socially desirable but under-consumed in a free market
Summary: Merit goods like education are socially beneficial but under-consumed via free markets. We analyze intervention rationales and policy impacts on access and welfare.

Blog Title: Event: The outcome that is being tested for in a probability experiment
Summary: An event in probability theory is a subset of possible outcomes from a random experiment's sample space.

Blog Title: Equivalent fraction: Fractions with different numerators and denominators
Summary: The result of multiplying (or dividing) the top and bottom of a fraction by the same value.

Blog Title: Equation of a line: Lines relate coordinates via equations
Summary: A formula that shows how the x-coordinate is related to the y-coordinate, for any point on a line.

Blog Title: Empty set: A set with no elements
Summary: The empty set contains nothing, is foundational to mathematics, and is a subset of all sets.

Blog Title: Discount: the amount by which an original selling price is reduced
Summary: A reduction from an original price, expressed as a percentage or fixed amount.

Blog Title: Differentiation is the calculus process of finding a function's instantaneous rate of change
Summary: the process of finding a derived function, which tells you the gradient of the function at a point on the curve.

Blog Title: The difference of squares is a factoring pattern
Summary: A method of factorizing (putting into brackets) one squared term subtracted from another.

Blog Title: Derivative of function: Rate of change's precise tool.
Summary: The derivative of function (or derivative) of a constant factor and/or a product that gives the rate of change at any point on a graph.

Blog Title: Cyclic quadrilateral: A quadrilateral whose vertices all exactly touch the circumference of a circle
Summary: A quadrilateral inscribed in a circle. Its opposite angles are supplementary, and related by Ptolemy’s theorem.

Blog Title: Cumulative frequency: A ‘running total’ of the frequencies
Summary: Cumulative frequency sums data progressively. It shows how many observations fall below each successive value in a dataset.

Blog Title: Cost price: The price that a trader pays for goods
Summary: Cost price is the original amount paid for an item, serving as the baseline for calculating profit, loss, and markup in financial mathematics.

Blog Title: Cosine rule: A formula connecting the three sides of a triangle and one of the angles
Summary: The cosine rule generalizes Pythagoras, relating all triangle sides to one included angle. Essential for non-right triangles.

Blog Title: Cosine ratio compares adjacent side to hypotenuse in right triangles
Summary: For a given angle (other than the right-angle) in a right-angled triangle, the cosine ratio is the length of the side adjacent to the angle divided by the hypotenuse of the triangle.

Blog Title: Correlation: The relationship between bivariate data
Summary: Correlation quantifies the linear relationship between two variables, ranging from perfect positive (+1) to perfect negative (-1) association.

Blog Title: Conversion: Changing one quantity or unit into its equivalent in another unit
Summary: In mathematics, conversion changes a quantity's form (e.g., units, bases) while preserving its value.

Blog Title: Constant term: A term in an equation or expression that has a fixed numerical value
Summary: A fixed value that does not change. It is a number alone, without variables. Examples: 5, π, e.

Blog Title: Conditional probability: the probability of an event assuming that another has occurred
Summary: Conditional probability calculates event likelihood given prior information, fundamentally updating predictions based on new evidence.

Blog Title: Compound interest: interest paid on interest already earned and not just the original capital
Summary: Interest earns further interest, enabling exponential growth of principal through reinvested earnings over time.

Blog Title: Composite number: integer with more than two factors i.e. it has more factors than just 1 and itself
Summary: Composite numbers have more than two distinct positive divisors. They are fundamental to number theory, contrasting with primes. Example: 135 (5 × 3³).

Blog Title: Composite function: applying a function to a value and then another function to that result
Summary: A composite function applies one function's output as another's input, creating a new, nested mathematical operation.

Blog Title: Complementary angles: Two angles whose sum is 90 degrees
Summary: Two angles are complementary when their sum equals exactly 90 degrees. This fundamental geometric relationship is essential for solving problems in trigonometry and proofs.

Blog Title: Complement (of a set): set of objects that are not in a set, but which are part of the larger universal set
Summary: In set theory, the complement of a set contains all elements not in the original set, relative to a universal set.

Blog Title: Mathematics' common denominator is the shared foundational language of numbers and logic
Summary: A common value that two or more fractions need to be converted to in order to be able to add and/or subtract fractions.

Blog Title: A column vector is a matrix with a single column
Summary: Number pair notation used to describe a vector as the movement between two points: x units in the x-direction (left or right) and y units in the in the y-direction (up or down).

Blog Title: Co-interior angle: A pair of angles between the parallel lines on the same side of a transversal
Summary: Co-interior angles lie between parallel lines on the same side of a transversal. Their sum is always 180 degrees.

Blog Title: class interval: the group into which numeral data has been placed
Summary: Class intervals group continuous data into manageable ranges for statistical analysis, simplifying frequency distribution and pattern identification.

Blog Title: centre of rotation: the point around which a plane shape can rotate and show the same shape in different positions
Summary: Rotation's fixed point. It defines the central hub around which every other point in a figure turns.

Blog Title: bivariate data: two measurements, relating to an investigation, taken at the same time
Summary: Analyzing the relationship between two paired variables using correlation and visual scatter plots.

Blog Title: base: when working with indices, the base is the number that is being raised to a power
Summary: "135 is an odd, composite integer. Notably, it equals the sum of its first three positive cubes (1³+2³+3³+4³+5³)."

Blog Title: asymptote: a line that a graph approaches but never intersects
Summary: An asymptote is a line a curve perpetually approaches but never meets, defining a limit.

Blog Title: apex: in a pyramid, the apex is the point, above the base, at which all the sloping sides meet
Summary: The apex is a pyramid's vertex opposite its base, where all lateral faces and edges converge. It defines the pyramid's height.

Blog Title: Alternate Segment Theorem: The angle between a chord and tangent equals the angle in the alternate segment of a circle
Summary: When an angle is drawn between a tangent and a chord the alternate segment is the segment that the angle does not cross.

Blog Title: Rf Value (Retardation Factor): Quantifies compound migration in chromatography
Summary: In chromatography, a value that characterizes a compound's movement on a plate. Rf = (distance moved by compound) / (distance moved by solvent front).

Blog Title: Thin-Layer Chromatography (TLC) is a simple, fast analytical technique for separating and identifying chemical mixture
Summary: A chromatography technique where the stationary phase is a thin layer of adsorbent material (like silica gel) coated on a plate.

Blog Title: Stationary Phase: the stationary phase is the fixed material that selectively retains components
Summary: The phase that does not move in a chromatography system. The components of the mixture interact with this phase, leading to separation.

Blog Title: The chemical shift (δ) identifies a nucleus's local magnetic environment
Summary: In NMR spectroscopy, the resonant frequency of a nucleus relative to a standard in a magnetic field. It is measured in parts per million (ppm).

Blog Title: Carbon-13 (¹³C) NMR Spectroscopy: identifies carbon atoms in molecules by their chemical environment
Summary: A type of NMR spectroscopy that observes the carbon-13 isotope, providing information about the carbon skeleton of organic molecules.

Blog Title: Proton (¹H) NMR Spectroscopy: reveals molecular structure by analyzing hydrogen environments in compounds
Summary: A specific type of NMR spectroscopy that observes hydrogen-1 nuclei within the molecules of a substance, providing information about the number and environment of hydrogen atoms.

Blog Title: Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) Spectroscopy
Summary: An analytical technique that exploits the magnetic properties of certain atomic nuclei to determine the structure of organic compounds.

Blog Title: The mobile phase is the fluid that carries analytes through the chromatography system
Summary: The phase that moves in a chromatography system, carrying the components of the mixture with it. It can be a gas or a liquid.

Blog Title: Gas-Liquid Chromatography separates volatile mixtures
Summary: A type of chromatography where the mobile phase is a gas and the stationary phase is a liquid retained on an inert solid support.

Blog Title: Chromatography: A chemical technique for separating mixtures into their components
Summary: A laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture by passing it in a solution or suspension through a medium in which the components move at different rates.

Blog Title: Analytical chemistry identifies and quantifies matter
Summary: The branch of chemistry concerned with the separation, identification, and quantification of the chemical components of materials.

Blog Title: Analytical techniques identify, characterize, and quantify matter in all chemical disciplines
Summary: Analytical techniques identify and quantify chemical compounds, enabling research, quality control, and environmental monitoring.

Blog Title: Synthetic Route: A novel synthetic route to the target compound was developed
Summary: A planned sequence of chemical reactions that converts readily available starting materials into a desired target molecule.

Blog Title: Private sector: part of the economy owned and operated by private individuals and firms
Summary: Economy sector owned/operated by private individuals & firms, distinct from government control.

Blog Title: Public sector: part of the economy owned and controlled by the government
Summary: Economy's government-owned segment. Provides essential services, infrastructure, and strategic goods for public welfare and national development.

Blog Title: Mixed economy: an economy combining both market forces and government intervention
Summary: Mixed economies blend market forces with government regulation to achieve efficiency and social welfare, balancing private enterprise and public intervention.

Blog Title: Rationing: government restriction on access to goods when demand exceeds supply
Summary: Govt limits goods access when demand > supply. Explores ethical, economic impacts across crises, wars, and resource scarcity.

Blog Title: Central planning: government determination of what to produce, how to produce and for whom to produce
Summary: Government centrally plans production, methods, and distribution, contrasting market-based allocation and its economic effects.

Blog Title: Planned economy (command economy): an economy where the government makes all major decisions about resource allocation
Summary: Consumers' spending choices direct production, ensuring market output aligns with true demand, defining the principle of consumer sovereignty.

Blog Title: Consumer sovereignty: situation where consumers determine what is produced through their spending choices
Summary: Consumers' spending choices direct production, ensuring market output aligns with true demand, defining the principle of consumer sovereignty.

Blog Title: Profit motive: incentive for firms to produce in order to earn profit
Summary: Profit motive drives firm production for profit—key incentive in market economics.

Blog Title: Price mechanism: system where prices act as signals to allocate resources
Summary: Prices guide production & consumption, allocating scarce resources through supply & demand signals in a market system.

Blog Title: Market economy: an economy where resource allocation is determined mainly by market forces of demand and supply
Summary: Market economy: resource allocation driven by supply & demand forces, not central planning.

Blog Title: Economic system: the method used by a country to organise production and allocation of resources
Summary: Ways countries manage resources, production, and goods/services distribution, from planned to market systems.

Blog Title: Racemate (or Racemic Mixture): A 50:50 mixture of two enantiomers of a chiral molecule
Summary: Racemates are 1:1 mixtures of mirror-image molecules. They lack optical activity but have distinct physical properties from their pure enantiomers.

Blog Title: Pure Enantiomer: A sample of a chiral molecule that consists of only one of the two possible enantiomers
Summary: A pure enantiomer is a stereoisomer composed exclusively of one chiral molecular form, devoid of its mirror-image counterpart.

Blog Title: Innovation: developing new ideas, products or production methods
Summary: Driving progress: Innovation is the engine behind new ideas, products, and methods, fueling growth and solving tomorrow’s challenges today.

Blog Title: Risk taking: willingness of an entrepreneur to invest money despite uncertainty
Summary: Venturing capital into the unknown defines entrepreneurial risk-taking, driving innovation and growth amid uncertainty.

Blog Title: Surplus: production beyond personal needs that can be traded
Summary: Production surplus enables trade, forming economies. This study explores its role from early barter to modern markets, analyzing its economic and social impacts in 135 characters.

Blog Title: Pharmaceutical: A chemical substance used in the treatment, cure, prevention, or diagnosis of disease
Summary: Pharmaceutical chemistry designs, synthesizes, and develops drug molecules to diagnose, treat, and cure diseases.

Blog Title: Productivity: output per worker or per unit of input
Summary: Productivity measures efficiency in converting inputs into outputs. Key factors: technology, skills, and processes. It drives economic growth and living standards.

Blog Title: Enantiomers are non-superimposable mirror-image molecules
Summary: One of a pair of stereoisomers that are mirror images of each other but are not identical, much like a left and right hand.

Blog Title: Division of labour: breaking production into separate tasks so each worker specialises in one task
Summary: Divide labour: specialised tasks boost productivity. Promotes efficiency, skill mastery, innovation, yet risks monotony. Vital for economic growth.

Blog Title: Specialisation: concentration on specific tasks, goods or services to increase efficiency
Summary: Specializing in tasks boosts efficiency by channeling focus into core activities. This creates productivity gains.

Blog Title: Chirality: molecules that are non-superimposable mirror images
Summary: A property of a molecule that is not superimposable on its mirror image. Such molecules are often called chiral.

Blog Title: Human capital: skills, knowledge and experience of workers that increase productivity
Summary: Investing in workforce human capital—skills, knowledge, experience—boosts productivity, innovation, and long-term economic competitiveness.

Blog Title: Profit: reward earned by enterprise for taking risks
Summary: Profit: reward for entrepreneurial risk-taking, driving innovation and economic growth.

Blog Title: Enterprise: organisation of the other factors of production and willingness to take risks in business
Summary: Enterprise: risk-taking and organization in production

Blog Title: Return on capital: financial reward earned from using or renting capital
Summary: Capital yields financial reward when utilized or rented; this return measures investment efficiency.

Blog Title: Polymer Deductions: Polymers often yield unpredictable degradation fragments
Summary: The process of working out the structure of a monomer or a section of the polymer chain from the polymer's repeat unit or its products of hydrolysis.

Blog Title: Capital (physical capital): man-made resources like machinery, buildings and equipment used in production
Summary: Abstract: Physical capital: man-made productive assets—machinery, buildings, equipment—essential for economic output and growth.

Blog Title: Synthetic polyamides are versatile polymers with strong amide linkages
Summary: A man-made polyamide, such as nylon, typically formed by the reaction of a diamine with a dicarboxylic acid derivative.

Blog Title: Wage: payment received for labour services
Summary: Compensation for labour. Covers forms, determinants, and economic/social significance of wages.

Blog Title: Degradable Polymer: A polymer that can be broken down
Summary: Degradable polymers are designed with cleavable bonds to break down via hydrolysis or enzymes.

Blog Title: Labour: human effort and skills used in production
Summary: Human labour: essential skilled effort in production, driving economic value and societal progress through applied knowledge and physical work.

Blog Title: Rent: income earned from ownership of land
Summary: Income earned from land ownership, its economic role, and distribution.

Blog Title: Land: natural resources such as soil, water, minerals and climate
Summary: Land provides essential natural resources—soil, water, minerals, and climate—forming the foundation for all life and human systems.

Blog Title: Peptides are short chains of amino acids
Summary: Short chains of amino acids linked by peptide bonds. They are formed by a condensation reaction between the amino group of one amino acid and the carboxyl group of another.

Blog Title: Factors of production: resources used to produce goods and services
Summary: Land, labor, capital: the essential inputs for all economic output.

Blog Title: Very long run: time period in which all factors and key external inputs (technology, regulation, etc.) can change
Summary: Very long run: all factors—technology, regulation, resources—are variable. This transforms analysis and policy for sustained growth.

Blog Title: Long run: time period in which all factors of production can change
Summary: Time flexible: all inputs adjust in long run. No fixed constraints shape production capacity. Firms fully adapt.

Blog Title: Electrophoresis separates charged particles in a fluid using an electric field
Summary: A technique used to separate charged molecules, such as amino acids or peptides, based on their movement in an electric field.

Blog Title: Short run: time period in which only some factors of production can change
Summary: Short run: constraints shape firm choices. Limited flexibility, adapting resources to meet shifting market demands.

Blog Title: Margin / marginal analysis: analysis of the effect of a small change in one variable on other variables
Summary: Marginal analysis: measuring how small changes in one variable affect related outcomes in economics and decision-making.

Blog Title: Amino acids are organic molecules containing both amine and carboxyl groups
Summary: Molecules that contain both a basic amino group (-NH₂) and an acidic carboxylic acid group (-COOH).

Blog Title: Amines are organic nitrogen compounds derived from ammonia
Summary: Organic compounds derived from ammonia (NH₃) by replacing one or more hydrogen atoms with alkyl or aryl groups. Classified as primary (1°), secondary (2°), or tertiary (3°).

Blog Title: Amides: key organic carbonyl compounds with C(=O)N bonds
Summary: Organic compounds with the functional group -CONH₂. They can be primary (RCONH₂), secondary (RCONHR'), or tertiary (RCONR'R'').

Blog Title: Nitrogen compounds form diverse
Summary: Nitrogen compounds are essential in life, materials, and explosives, from ammonia and proteins to synthetic dyes and energetic materials.

Blog Title: Polyester: A polymer in which the monomer units are linked by ester bonds 
Summary: Polyester is a synthetic polymer, formed by ester functional group condensation reactions.

Blog Title: Polyamides are polymers with amide linkages
Summary: A polymer in which the monomer units are linked by amide bonds (-CONH-). They can be synthetic (e.g., nylon) or natural (e.g., proteins).

Blog Title: Condensation polymerization forms polymers
Summary: A polymerization reaction in which two different monomers react together, losing a small molecule (like H₂O or HCl) to form a long-chain polymer.

Blog Title: Benzene's exceptional stability arises from its aromatic
Summary: Benzene is more stable than a theoretical molecule with three isolated double bonds.

Blog Title: Phenyl Group: The functional group derived from benzene by removing one hydrogen atom
Summary: A phenyl group is a benzene ring minus one hydrogen.

Blog Title: Phenol: An aromatic compound where a hydroxyl (-OH) group is directly attached to a benzene ring
Summary: Phenol (C₆H₅OH) is an aromatic organic compound. It is a weak acid, a precursor to plastics, and a classic antiseptic. Toxic and corrosive in concentrated form.

Blog Title: Ceteris paribus: assumption that “other things remain equal” when analysing one change at a time
Summary: Ceteris paribus isolates a single variable's effect by assuming all other factors remain constant, a foundational tool for clear analysis.

Blog Title: Normative statement: a value-based economic opinion that cannot be tested
Summary: Economic policy advice rests on normative statements—untestable value judgments that shape all recommended goals and actions.

Blog Title: Positive statement: a factual economic statement that can be tested or proven true or false
Summary: Positive economic claims: testable factual statements validated or refuted by evidence.

Blog Title: Model: simplified representation of real economic behaviour used to explain and predict outcomes
Summary: Economic models as simplified representations of real behavior, used to explain and predict outcomes.

Blog Title: Social science: a science that studies human behaviour and decision-making
Summary: Human behavior science: analyzing decisions, interactions, and societal patterns to understand and predict collective human action.

Blog Title: Macroeconomics: study of the whole economy and aggregates such as inflation, GDP and unemployment
Summary: Macroeconomics analyzes economy-wide aggregates like GDP, inflation, and unemployment to understand and guide national economic policy.

Blog Title: Nitration adds a nitro group (-NO₂) to a molecule
Summary: An electrophilic substitution reaction where a nitro group (-NO₂) is introduced into a benzene ring, using a mixture of concentrated nitric and sulfuric acids.

Blog Title: Halogen Carrier (Halogenation Catalyst)
Summary: A catalyst such as AlBr₃ or AlCl₃ required for the electrophilic substitution of a halogen atom into a benzene ring.

Blog Title: Friedel-Crafts acylation installs acyl groups onto aromatic rings using Lewis acid catalysts
Summary: An electrophilic substitution reaction where an acyl group (R-C=O⁺) is introduced onto a benzene ring, using an acyl chloride and AlCl₃ catalyst.

Blog Title: Microeconomics: study of individual markets, firms and households
Summary: Microeconomic analysis of individual markets, firm decisions, and household choices to explain resource allocation.

Blog Title: Electrophilic Substitution: Aromatic rings undergo attack by electron-seeking reagents
Summary: The characteristic reaction of benzene and arenes, where an electrophile attacks the electron-rich ring, substituting for a hydrogen atom.

Blog Title: Economics: study of how scarce resources are allocated to satisfy human needs and wants
Summary: Economics studies how scarce resources are allocated to meet human needs and wants.

Blog Title: Luxuries: non-essential goods and services that increase comfort or pleasure
Summary: Non-essential comforts that enhance life, shaping economies and desires.

Blog Title: An electrophile is a reagent attracted to electrons
Summary: An atom or group of atoms that is attracted to an electron-rich centre and accepts an electron pair to form a new covalent bond.

Blog Title: Bromination is the chemical addition of bromine to a compound
Summary: A substitution reaction where a bromine atom is introduced into a molecule. For benzene, this requires a halogen carrier catalyst.

Blog Title: Scale of preference: ranking of wants from most important to least important
Summary: Scale of preference: Ranking human wants by priority. Influences economic choices and resource allocation, guiding rational decision-making.

Blog Title: Government intervention: actions taken by the state to influence production or income distribution
Summary: State actions influencing production or distribution. Key effects, types, and economic debate.

Blog Title: Benzene: a planar, hexagonal hydrocarbon (C₆H₆) with delocalized pi electrons
Summary: An aromatic hydrocarbon with the molecular formula C₆H₆, characterized by a planar ring structure with delocalised π electrons.

Blog Title: Equality / Social equality: fair distribution of income and wealth among members of society
Summary: Equal income/wealth distribution ensures societal fairness, fostering justice and stability for all members.

Blog Title: Aromatic Compound: A class of compounds that contain a benzene ring or other rings with similar bonding and stability characteristics
Summary: Aromatic compounds are cyclic, planar molecules with delocalized π electrons, granting unusual stability and reactivity.

Blog Title: Economic freedom: ability of individuals and firms to make their own economic decisions
Summary: People freely choosing economic actions drives prosperity and innovation.

Blog Title: Trade-off: compromise in which gaining more of one thing requires giving up part of another
Summary: Trade-offs: essential concept where more of one good necessitates less of another. Governs economics, ecology, engineering.

Blog Title: Resource allocation: distribution of limited resources among competing uses
Summary: "Optimizing limited resource allocation among competing needs. Strategies for maximizing efficiency, equity, and impact in a constrained environment."

Blog Title: Consumption: using goods and services to satisfy needs and wants
Summary: Buy goods & services to meet needs & desires. Key to economics & identity. Shapes markets, culture, & environment.

Blog Title: Arene: A general term for an aromatic hydrocarbon containing one or more benzene rings
Summary: Arenes are aromatic hydrocarbons with delocalized π-electrons in planar rings, notably benzene. They undergo substitution reactions.

Blog Title: Aromatic Chemistry: The study of cyclic, planar compounds with delocalized π-electrons
Summary: Aromatic compounds, like benzene, have unique stability and reactivity due to cyclic, planar systems with delocalized π-electrons.

Blog Title: Optical isomers are non-superimposable mirror images, differing in how they rotate plane-polarized light
Summary: A form of stereoisomerism where two isomers (non-superimposable mirror images) rotate plane-polarized light in opposite directions.

Blog Title: Cis-trans isomers have identical atoms but different spatial arrangements due to restricted bond rotation
Summary: A form of stereoisomerism in which atoms or groups of atoms are arranged differently on either side of a bond or plane in a molecule or complex.

Blog Title: The chelate effect: multidentate ligands bind metal ions more strongly than monodentate ones
Summary: The increased stability of a complex ion containing multidentate ligands compared to similar complexes with unidentate ligands.

Blog Title: Multidentate ligands form stable, chelating complexes by binding metals through multiple donor sites
Summary: A ligand that can donate more than two lone pairs of electrons to a central metal ion (e.g., EDTA⁴⁻).

Blog Title: A bidentate ligand binds a metal ion using two donor atoms simultaneously
Summary: A ligand that can donate two lone pairs of electrons to the central metal ion, forming two coordinate bonds (e.g., 1,2-diaminoethane, NH₂CH₂CH₂NH₂).

Blog Title: Stability constants (K_stab) quantify complex formation in solution
Summary: The equilibrium constant for the formation of a complex ion in a solvent from its constituent ions or molecules.

Blog Title: Ligand Substitution: A reaction in which one ligand in a complex ion is replaced by another ligand
Summary: Ligand substitution is a fundamental reaction where one coordinated ligand is replaced by another in a metal complex's inner sphere.

Blog Title: Transition Element: An element that forms at least one stable ion with a partially filled d-subshell
Summary: Metallic elements forming colorful compounds, variable oxidation states, and acting as essential catalysts.

Blog Title: Ligand: Ligands are molecules or ions that bind to a central metal atom, forming coordination complexes
Summary: An atom, ion, or molecule that donates a pair of electrons to a central metal ion to form a coordinate (dative covalent) bond.

Blog Title: Complex Ion: A central metal ion surrounded by coordinately bonded molecules or anions, known as ligands
Summary: Coordination complexes formed by a central metal ion bonded to surrounding ligands, altering reactivity, color, and solubility.

Blog Title: Standard Gibbs Free Energy Change (ΔGᶿ): The Gibbs free energy change for a reaction under standard conditions
Summary: Standard Gibbs Free Energy (ΔG°) predicts reaction spontaneity at standard conditions. A negative value indicates a thermodynamically favorable process.

Blog Title: Universe: In thermodynamics, this refers to the system plus the surroundings
Summary: The universe's chemistry, forged in stars, reveals elemental origins, molecular clouds, and life's building blocks across cosmic evolution.

Blog Title: Surroundings: Everything outside the system
Summary: The surroundings are everything external to the defined chemical system, where energy and matter can be exchanged during a process.

Blog Title: The Second Law of Thermodynamics: The total entropy of a system and its surroundings always increases for a spontaneous change
Summary: Entropy of an isolated system never decreases. This law dictates spontaneity, disorder, and the one-way direction of all chemical processes.

Blog Title: A reaction feasible in thermodynamics and kinetics under specified
Summary: A reaction that is capable of occurring, as predicted by a negative value for the Gibbs free energy change (ΔG < 0).

Blog Title: Entropy Change (ΔS): The difference in entropy between the products and the reactants in a chemical reaction
Summary: Entropy (ΔS) quantifies molecular disorder. Reactions increase ΔS by producing gas or dissolving solids, indicating spontaneity.

Blog Title: Standard Entropy (Sᶿ): The absolute entropy of one mole of a substance under standard conditions
Summary: Standard Entropy (S°) measures a substance’s disorder. Absolute zero defines its baseline; complexity and state drive increases in molecular randomness.

Blog Title: Spontaneous Change: A change that, once started, will continue without any external influence
Summary: Spontaneous processes in chemistry, like heat flow, proceed without external energy input, dictated by entropy and enthalpy changes.

Blog Title: Gibbs Free Energy Change (ΔG)
Summary: The maximum amount of useful work that can be obtained from a reaction at constant temperature and pressure. ΔG = ΔH - TΔS.

Blog Title: Entropy (S) quantifies a system’s molecular disorder or randomness
Summary: A measure of the number of ways in which particles and their energy can be arranged, or a measure of the disorder of a system.

Blog Title: Production: process of using resources to create goods and services
Summary: Transforming inputs into outputs efficiently, the production process creates value for society.

Blog Title: Goods and services: products and activities that satisfy needs and wants
Summary: Products and activities that meet human needs and wants, driving all economic systems and exchanges.

Blog Title: Opportunity cost: the next best alternative that is forgone when a choice is made
Summary: Choosing forces sacrifice. Opportunity cost is the value of the next-best option you must give up with every decision.

Blog Title: The overall order of reaction is the sum of the exponents of the reactant concentrations in the experimentally determined rate law
Summary: The sum of the powers of the concentration terms in the rate equation. For rate = k[A]^m[B]^n, the overall order is m + n.

Blog Title: Rate-Determining Step: The slowest step in a multi-step (complex) reaction mechanism
Summary: A reaction’s slowest, highest-energy step dictates its overall rate and kinetic profile. This bottleneck is the rate-determining step.

Blog Title: Rate Equation: The rate equation models reaction speed using reactant concentrations and a constant
Summary: An equation that shows the relationship between the reaction rate and the concentrations of the reactants, each raised to a power (the order).

Blog Title: Rate Constant (k): The constant of proportionality in the rate equation
Summary: Rate constant (k) quantifies reaction speed, determined by temperature and activation energy via the Arrhenius equation.

Blog Title: Order of Reaction (with respect to a reactant)
Summary: The power to which the concentration of a reactant is raised in the rate equation.

Blog Title: Half-life (of a reaction): The time taken for the concentration of a reactant to decrease to half of its initial value
Summary: The time required for half the reactant concentration to decompose. A fundamental measure of reaction kinetics and rate.

Blog Title: Partition Coefficient (Kpc): The ratio of the concentrations of a solute in two immiscible solvents at equilibrium
Summary: Kpc predicts how a solute partitions between two solvents, critical for pharmacology and environmental chemistry's distribution studies.

Blog Title: Combining Half-Cells: Connecting two different half-cells to form an electrochemical cell, allowing electrons to flow
Summary: Combining two half-cells, via a salt bridge, creates a galvanic cell that converts chemical energy to electrical energy spontaneously.

Blog Title: A half-cell is a single electrode immersed in an electrolyte, enabling electron transfer
Summary: A metal in contact with a solution of its own ions, which constitutes one part of an electrochemical cell.

Blog Title: The standard electrode potential measures a species' inherent tendency to gain or lose electrons
Summary: The electrode potential of a half-cell measured under standard conditions (298 K, 100 kPa, 1 mol dm⁻³ solutions).

Blog Title: Electrode Potential (E): A measure of the tendency of a species to gain or lose electrons
Summary: The driving force for a reduction reaction. It quantitatively predicts a substance's tendency to gain electrons.

Blog Title: Quantitative electrolysis calculates substance mass using electrical current, time
Summary: Calculations involving the masses or volumes of substances produced during electrolysis, based on the amount of electricity passed.

Blog Title: Cathode: The negative electrode, Reduction occurs here
Summary: The cathode is the electrode where reduction occurs, gaining electrons during electrochemical reactions.

Blog Title: Anode: The positive electrode, Oxidation occurs here
Summary: The anode is the electrode where oxidation occurs, releasing electrons to the external circuit.

Blog Title: Electrode: A conductor through which electricity enters or leaves a system during electrolysis
Summary: An electrical conductor connecting non-metallic circuit parts, like an electrolyte, to transfer electrons.

Blog Title: Electrolytes are substances that produce an electrically conductive solution when dissolved in water
Summary: A substance that, when molten or dissolved in water, conducts electricity and is decomposed in the process. Electrolytes contain free-moving ions.

Blog Title: Electrolysis: The process in which electrical energy is used to drive a non-spontaneous chemical reaction
Summary: Using electrical energy to drive a non-spontaneous chemical reaction, decomposing compounds into elements.

Blog Title: Electrochemistry: The branch of chemistry that deals with the interconversion of electrical energy and chemical energy
Summary: Electrochemistry studies the interconversion of electrical energy and chemical reactions in systems.

Blog Title: Lattice Energy (ΔHₗₑₜₜ) measures the strength of ionic bonds in a crystalline solid compound
Summary: Lattice energy (ΔHₗₑₜₜ) is the energy released when gaseous ions form one mole of a solid ionic crystal.

Blog Title:  Enthalpy Change of Solution (ΔHₛₒₗ)
Summary: The enthalpy change when one mole of an ionic solid dissolves in a large enough amount of water that the ions no longer interact.

Blog Title: Enthalpy Change of Atomisation (ΔHₐₜ)
Summary: The enthalpy change when one mole of gaseous atoms is formed from an element in its standard state under standard conditions.

Blog Title: Electron affinity measures an atom's energy change when gaining an electron
Summary: The enthalpy change when one mole of electrons is added to one mole of gaseous atoms to form one mole of gaseous negative ions (anions).

Blog Title: Born-Haber Cycle: A thermochemical cycle that applies Hess's Law to calculate the lattice energy of an ionic compound
Summary: The Born-Haber cycle calculates ionic lattice energy using a thermochemical pathway.

Blog Title: Atomisation: The process of converting a substance into separate, free atoms in the gaseous state
Summary: Atomisation is the process of converting a substance into a cloud of separate, gaseous atoms.

Blog Title: Thermodynamics governs energy transfer
Summary: Thermodynamics explores energy (heat, work) in chemical processes. It predicts reaction spontaneity, direction, and equilibrium using fundamental laws.

Blog Title: Nucleophilic Addition-Elimination: A nucleophile attacks an electrophile 
Summary: A two-step mechanism common for carboxylic acid derivatives (like acyl chlorides) where a nucleophile first adds to the carbonyl carbon, followed by the elimination of a leaving group.

Blog Title: Acyl Chloride: A derivative of a carboxylic acid where the -OH group is replaced by a -Cl atom
Summary: Acyl chlorides are highly reactive carboxylic acid derivatives used for synthesizing amides, esters, and ketones.

Blog Title: Infrared (IR) Spectroscopy: An analytical technique that identifies types of chemical bonds in a molecule by producing an absorption spectrum
Summary: Infrared spectroscopy identifies chemical functional groups by their characteristic molecular vibration frequencies.

Blog Title: Hydroxynitrile (Cyanohydrin): The product of the nucleophilic addition of hydrogen cyanide (HCN) to an aldehyde or ketone
Summary: Hydroxynitriles, or cyanohydrins, are functional group combinations of hydroxyl and nitrile, valuable in organic synthesis.

Blog Title: Hydrogen Cyanide (HCN) is a weak acid crucial in industrial synthesis and fumigation
Summary: A nucleophile that adds to aldehydes and ketones to form compounds called hydroxynitriles (or cyanohydrins).

Blog Title: Tollens' test distinguishes aldehydes from ketones via silver mirror deposition on a test tube
Summary: A test used to distinguish aldehydes from ketones, often called the "silver mirror test." Aldehydes reduce [Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺ ions to metallic silver.

Blog Title: Fehling's test identifies aldehydes
Summary: A test used to distinguish between aldehydes and ketones. Aldehydes reduce the deep blue Cu²⁺ ions to a brick-red precipitate of Cu₂O.

Blog Title: Tri-iodomethane (Iodoform) Test: A chemical test detecting compounds with a CH₃C=O group
Summary: A chemical test used to identify methyl ketones (ketones with the structure RCOCH₃) and acetaldehyde (ethanal).

Blog Title: The reduction of carbonyls increases hydrogen content
Summary: A reaction in which aldehydes are reduced to primary alcohols (RCHO → RCH₂OH) and ketones are reduced to secondary alcohols.

Blog Title: Nucleophilic Addition: A nucleophile attacks an electron-deficient carbon
Summary: A characteristic reaction of aldehydes and ketones in which a nucleophile attacks the positively charged carbon of the carbonyl group.

Blog Title: Aldehydes, characterized by a carbonyl group bonded to hydrogen
Summary: A carbonyl compound in which the carbonyl carbon atom is bonded to at least one hydrogen atom. The general formula is RCHO.

Blog Title: Carbonyl compounds, featuring C=O
Summary: Ubiquitous in nature and industry, carbonyls are a fundamental functional group central to countless chemical reactions and life itself.

Blog Title: Saponification: The alkaline hydrolysis of esters with base to produce soap and glycerol from fats and oils
Summary: The alkaline hydrolysis of an ester (specifically fats and oils) to produce a carboxylic acid salt (soap) and an alcohol.

Blog Title: Condensation Reaction: A chemical union where two molecules join
Summary: A chemical reaction in which two molecules combine to form a larger molecule, with the loss of a small molecule like water or HCl.

Blog Title: Dehydration: An elimination reaction where a water molecule is removed from a molecule
Summary: A chemical reaction where a molecule loses water, often forming a new, unsaturated compound.

Blog Title: Reflux: A technique where vapors are condensed and returned to the reaction vessel for greater yield
Summary: The process of boiling and condensing vapors back to enhance reaction efficiency and separation.

Blog Title: Fermentation: Biochemical catalysis employing enzymes from microorganisms to transform organic compounds
Summary: A biological process where microorganisms, such as yeast, break down sugars to produce ethanol and carbon dioxide in the absence of oxygen.

Blog Title: Hydroxyl Group: The -OH functional group found in alcohols
Summary: The hydroxyl group is a functional unit defining alcohols and phenols through its oxygen-hydrogen bond.

Blog Title: Esterification: The chemical reaction between a carboxylic acid and an alcohol to form an ester and water
Summary: Esterification chemically combines a carboxylic acid and an alcohol, forming an ester and water.

Blog Title: Esters: Pleasant-smelling organic compounds
Summary: An organic compound formed in a reaction between a carboxylic acid and an alcohol. Esters have the functional group (-COO-).

Blog Title: Carboxylic Acid: A homologous series of organic compounds containing the carboxyl functional group (-COOH)
Summary: Carboxylic acids are organic compounds characterized by the presence of the carboxyl functional group (-COOH).

Blog Title:  Alcohol: A homologous series of organic compounds containing the hydroxyl functional group (-OH) attached to a carbon atom
Summary: An organic compound with a hydroxyl group bonded to a saturated carbon atom.

Blog Title: Tertiary halogenoalkanes feature a halogen on a carbon bonded to three alkyl groups
Summary: A halogenoalkane where the carbon atom bonded to the halogen is itself attached to three other carbon atoms.

Blog Title: A primary halogenoalkane has the halogen bonded to a carbon attached to one other carbon
Summary: A halogenoalkane where the carbon atom bonded to the halogen is itself only attached to one other carbon atom.

Blog Title: Leaving Group: An atom or group that departs with a bond's electrons during a substitution reaction
Summary: An atom or group of atoms that is displaced with a pair of electrons in a substitution or elimination reaction

Blog Title: Carbocation: A carbon atom with a positive charge
Summary: An organic ion containing a positively charged carbon atom. Carbocations are intermediates in the Sₙ1 mechanism.

Blog Title: The Sₙ2 mechanism is a concerted, one-step nucleophilic substitution
Summary: (Substitution, Nucleophilic, Bimolecular). A one-step, concerted mechanism for nucleophilic substitution.

Blog Title: The Sₙ1 mechanism is a two-step
Summary: (Substitution, Nucleophilic, Unimolecular). A two-step mechanism for nucleophilic substitution, involving a carbocation intermediate.

Blog Title: Nucleophilic Substitution: An electron-rich species replaces a leaving group in a molecule
Summary: A fundamental reaction type for halogenoalkanes in which a nucleophile attacks the electron-deficient carbon atom, replacing the halogen atom.

Blog Title: Nucleophile: A chemical species that donates an electron pair to form a new covalent bond
Summary: A species that donates a pair of electrons to form a new covalent bond. Nucleophiles are attracted to electron-deficient regions.

Blog Title: Halogenoalkane (Haloalkane): are organic compounds where halogens replace hydrogen in alkanes
Summary: An organic compound in which one or more hydrogen atoms in an alkane have been replaced by halogen atoms.

Blog Title: Elimination Reaction: A molecule splits into two fragments
Summary: A type of organic reaction in which a small molecule (such as H₂O or HX) is removed from a larger molecule.

Blog Title: Unsaturated hydrocarbons possess double or triple carbon bonds
Summary: A hydrocarbon that contains at least one carbon-carbon double (C=C) or triple (C≡C) bond. Alkenes and alkynes are unsaturated.

Blog Title: Saturated Hydrocarbon: A hydrocarbon that contains only single bonds between carbon atoms
Summary: Saturated hydrocarbons contain only single carbon-carbon bonds, making them relatively unreactive alkanes.

Blog Title: Polymer: A very large molecule made up of many repeating monomer units joined together by covalent bonds
Summary: Large molecules of repeating units create essential natural and synthetic materials, from DNA to plastics.

Blog Title: Monomer: A small, reactive molecule that can be joined to other monomers to form a polymer
Summary: A molecule that can bind to others, forming a polymer's repeating structural unit.

Blog Title: Hydrocarbon: A compound containing only hydrogen and carbon atoms
Summary: Hydrocarbons are organic compounds consisting only of hydrogen and carbon atoms.

Blog Title: Cracking breaks large hydrocarbon molecules into smaller, more useful ones like petrol
Summary: The process in which long-chain hydrocarbon molecules from crude oil are broken down into shorter, more useful molecules.

Blog Title: Alkane: A homologous series of saturated hydrocarbons with the general formula CₙH₂ₙ₊₂
Summary: Saturated hydrocarbons. Single carbon-carbon bonds. Methane is simplest. Fuel sources and lubricants. Nonpolar, follow formula CₙH₂ₙ₊₂.

Blog Title: Addition polymerisation: Unsaturated monomer units open their double bonds to form a long-chain polymer
Summary: A chemical reaction in which many small monomer molecules join together to form a very large polymer molecule, with no other products.

Blog Title: Structural Formula: A formula that shows the atoms carbon by carbon
Summary: A structural formula depicts molecular connectivity and atomic arrangement beyond simple composition.

Blog Title: Structural Isomerism: Same atoms, different connectivity
Summary: A form of isomerism where molecules have the same molecular formula but different structural formulae (different connectivity of atoms).

Blog Title: Stereoisomers are molecules with the same connectivity but different spatial atomic arrangements
Summary: A form of isomerism where molecules have the same molecular formula and the same structural formula, but a different arrangement of atoms in space.

Blog Title: Species: A general term used for different particles such as atoms, ions, molecules, or free radicals
Summary: Identifiable atoms, molecules, or ions defined by composition and stability in a system.

Blog Title: A reaction mechanism proposes the step-by-step pathway by which reactants become products
Summary: A detailed, step-by-step description of how a chemical reaction occurs, showing the movement of electrons and the formation/breaking of bonds.

Blog Title: Organic Chemistry: The branch of chemistry that deals with carbon compounds
Summary: Organic Chemistry explores carbon-containing molecules, forming the basis of life and modern materials.

Blog Title: Molecular Formula: A formula that shows the actual number of atoms of each element in a molecule
Summary: A molecular formula uses elemental symbols and subscripts to denote the precise count of each atom type within a chemical compound.

Blog Title: A homologous series is a family of compounds with the same functional group and general formula
Summary: A family of organic compounds with the same functional group and general formula, where each member differs from the next by a -CH₂- group.

Blog Title: Functional Group: An atom or group of atoms that determines the main chemical properties of an organic compound
Summary: Molecules' reactive centers. Dictate chemical behavior, identity, and properties in organic synthesis and reactions.

Blog Title: Intro to Organic Chemistry: An introduction to carbon-containing compounds, their structures, properties
Summary: Exploring the molecular world of carbon. This introduction covers hydrocarbons, functional groups, isomerism, and essential reaction types.

Blog Title:  Nitrogen Oxides: A group of gases composed of nitrogen and oxygen atoms
Summary: Nitrogen oxides (NOx) are gases crucial in atmospheric chemistry. They are key precursors to smog, acid rain, and particulate matter, impacting air quality and health.

Blog Title: Nitrogen gas (N₂) is a stable, inert diatomic molecule constituting 78% of Earth's atmosphere
Summary: The diatomic molecule that makes up the majority of Earth's atmosphere. It is relatively unreactive due to a strong triple bond.

Blog Title: Ammonium Ion (NH₄⁺): A positively charged polyatomic ion formed by the protonation of ammonia
Summary: The ammonium ion (NH₄⁺) is a positively charged polyatomic ion, crucial in fertilizers and biological processes.

Blog Title: Ammonium Compounds: Ionic compounds containing the ammonium ion (NH₄⁺)
Summary: Nitrogen-based cations (NH₄⁺) form stable ammonium compounds with anions, crucial in fertilizers, pharmaceuticals, and surfactants.

Blog Title: Ammonia (NH₃): A colorless gas with a characteristic pungent smell
Summary: Ammonia (NH₃), a colorless gas, is a vital nitrogen source. Its polarity and hydrogen bonding give it high water solubility and a pungent odor.

Blog Title: Silver Halide: A compound formed between silver ions (Ag⁺) and halide ions
Summary: Silver halide compounds, like AgBr, are light-sensitive crystals crucial to traditional photography. They form latent images when exposed to light.

Blog Title: Relative Oxidising Power: Superior oxidizers readily accept electrons
Summary: A comparison of the ability of substances to act as oxidising agents. In Group 17, the oxidising power decreases down the group.

Blog Title: Halogens: The elements in Group 17 of the Periodic Table
Summary: Halogens are highly reactive nonmetals. Group 17 elements, they readily form salts with metals. Includes fluorine, chlorine, and bromine.

Blog Title: Halide Ions: Negatively charged ions formed by halogen atoms (F⁻, Cl⁻, Br⁻, I⁻)
Summary: Halide ions are anions of group 17, forming salts and participating in key nucleophilic substitution and precipitation reactions.

Blog Title: Group 17: The vertical column in the Periodic Table containing the elements fluorine (F), chlorine (Cl), bromine (Br), iodine (I), astatine (At)
Summary: Group 17 contains the reactive halogens, known for forming salts with various metals.

Blog Title: Thermal Decomposition: A chemical reaction where a compound breaks down into simpler substances when heated
Summary: The chemical breakdown of a single compound into two or more simpler substances through the application of heat energy.

Blog Title: Basicity: The ability of a substance to act as a base
Summary: Basicity measures a molecule's ability to accept a proton or donate an electron pair.

Blog Title: Solubility: The ability of a substance to dissolve in a solvent
Summary: Solubility is the property of a solute to dissolve in a solvent, forming a homogeneous solution at a specific temperature and pressure.

Blog Title: Precipitate: An insoluble solid that forms from a solution during a chemical reaction
Summary: In chemistry, a precipitate is an insoluble solid that forms from a solution during a chemical reaction, often seen as cloudiness or sediment.

Blog Title: Electrostatic Attraction: The force of attraction between positively and negatively charged particles
Summary: Electrostatic attraction is the fundamental force binding cations and anions in ionic bonds, governing lattice energy and compound stability.

Blog Title: Trend: A predictable pattern in properties
Summary: Periodic trends reveal predictable patterns in element properties across periods and down groups, guiding chemical understanding.

Blog Title: Hydroxides: Compounds containing the OH⁻ ion
Summary: Basic compounds containing the OH⁻ anion, often formed by metals like sodium, and are soluble in water.

Blog Title: Oxides: Compounds formed when an element combines with oxygen
Summary: Oxides are binary oxygen compounds. Classified as acidic, basic, or amphoteric, they are crucial in geology, industry, and environmental chemistry.

Blog Title: Reactions with Water: Chemical reactions where Group 2 elements react with water to form hydroxides and hydrogen gas
Summary: Water's reactivity varies, from violent metal explosions to gentle dissolution, defining a substance's chemical character.

Blog Title: Reactions with Oxygen: Chemical reactions where Group 2 elements combine with oxygen to form oxides
Summary: Reactions with oxygen, termed oxidation, are fundamental. They range from rapid combustion to slow rusting, often releasing energy as heat and light.

Blog Title: Physical properties are measurable characteristics of a substance
Summary: The characteristics of a substance that can be observed or measured without changing its chemical composition.

Blog Title: Group 2: Alkaline Earth Metals Shiny, reactive elements
Summary: A group of elements in the Periodic Table, also known as the alkaline earth metals, including beryllium (Be), magnesium (Mg), calcium (Ca), strontium (Sr), barium (Ba), radium (Ra).

Blog Title: Thermal Stability: The resistance of a compound to decomposition when heated
Summary: Thermal stability measures a material's ability to withstand temperature increase without chemical decomposition or phase change, crucial for safety and applications.

Blog Title: Simple molecules have low boiling points and exist as gases or liquids at room temperature
Summary: A structure where molecules are held together by strong covalent bonds, but the forces between molecules are weak intermolecular forces.

Blog Title: Period 3 elements exhibit progressive trends in bonding, structure, and electrical conductivity from Na to Ar
Summary: The elements in the third period of the Periodic Table: sodium (Na), magnesium (Mg), aluminium (Al), silicon (Si), phosphorus (P), sulfur (S), chlorine (Cl), argon (Ar).

Blog Title: Periodicity: The repeating pattern in the physical and chemical properties of the elements across a period
Summary: Periodicity describes the predictable, repeating patterns in the chemical and physical properties of elements, as revealed in the Periodic Table.

Blog Title: Neutral Oxide: An oxide that shows neither basic nor acidic properties and does not react with acids or bases
Summary: Neutral oxides exhibit neither acidic nor basic character. Common examples include carbon monoxide (CO), nitrous oxide (N₂O), and water (H₂O).

Blog Title: Metallic character is an element's electron-losing tendency
Summary: A set of properties associated with metals, such as lustre, malleability, ductility, and good electrical and thermal conductivity.

Blog Title: Hydrolysis: A chemical reaction in which a compound is broken down by water
Summary: A water molecule splits, breaking chemical bonds within another compound during hydrolysis.

Blog Title: Giant Metallic Lattice: A three-dimensional structure of positive metal ions surrounded by a 'sea' of delocalised electrons
Summary: A giant metallic lattice structure explains metals' conductivity, malleability, and high melting points.

Blog Title: Giant Ionic Lattice: A three-dimensional structure of oppositely charged ions held together by strong electrostatic forces (ionic bonds)
Summary: A giant ionic lattice is a vast, regular 3D structure of alternating cations and anions, strongly bonded by electrostatic attraction, dictating its properties.

Blog Title: Giant Covalent Structure: Immense lattices of strongly bonded atoms create high-melting
Summary: A vast network of atoms held together by strong covalent bonds, resulting in very high melting and boiling points (e.g., diamond, SiO₂).

Blog Title: Electrical Conductivity: A physical property that indicates how well a substance can conduct electricity
Summary: A measure of a solution's ability to conduct an electric current via ions.

Blog Title: Chloride: A compound containing chlorine
Summary: The chloride anion (Cl⁻) is essential for life and industry, forming salts like sodium chloride and stabilizing compounds.

Blog Title: Basic Oxide: An oxide that reacts with water to form a basic solution and with acids to form a salt
Summary: A metal oxide that reacts with an acid in a neutralization reaction, producing a salt and water. pH > 7.

Blog Title: Amphoteric: Describing a substance that can react with both acids and bases
Summary: Amphoteric substances exhibit dual chemical behavior, reacting as both acids and bases. Examples include water, amino acids, and aluminum hydroxide.

Blog Title: Acidic Oxide: Oxides of nonmetals that react with water to form acids and with bases
Summary: An acidic oxide is a nonmetal oxide that produces an acid in aqueous solution, neutralizing bases to form a salt and water.

Blog Title: Acid: A substance that can donate a proton (H⁺ ion)
Summary: In chemistry, acids are proton donors, characterized by a sour taste, low pH, and turning blue litmus paper red. They react with bases.

Blog Title: Homogeneous Catalyst: A catalyst that is in the same physical state (phase) as the reactants
Summary: Homogeneous catalysts function in the same phase as reactants, offering superior selectivity and mechanistic control, facilitating optimized chemical synthesis and industrial processes.

Blog Title: Heterogeneous catalysts are solid substances that accelerate chemical reactions between fluid reactants
Summary: A catalyst that is in a different physical state (phase) from the reactants (e.g., a solid catalyst for gaseous reactants).

Blog Title: Catalysis: The process of increasing the rate of a reaction using a catalyst
Summary: Catalysis is the acceleration of a chemical reaction by a catalyst, which remains unchanged. It is fundamental to life and industry.

Blog Title: Catalyst: A substance that increases the rate of a chemical reaction by providing an alternative reaction pathway with a lower activation energy
Summary: Accelerates reactions without being consumed. The essential spark for molecular transformation and efficient chemical processes.

Blog Title: Weak Acid: An acid that only partially dissociates into its ions in aqueous solution, establishing an equilibrium
Summary: A weak acid only partially ionizes in aqueous solution, creating an equilibrium between the intact acid and its ions.

Blog Title: Strong Acid: An acid that completely dissociates into its ions in aqueous solution
Summary: A strong acid is a substance that ionizes completely in an aqueous solution, resulting in a very low pH and a high concentration of H₃O⁺ ions.

Blog Title: Reversible Reaction: A reaction in which the products can react together to re-form the original reactants
Summary: A reversible reaction proceeds in both forward and reverse directions simultaneously, eventually reaching a state of dynamic chemical equilibrium.

Blog Title: pH: A logarithmic measure of the hydrogen ion concentration
Summary: The pH scale quantifies the concentration of hydrogen ions in a solution, determining its acidic or basic character.

Blog Title: Partial Pressure: The pressure that a gas in a mixture would exert if it alone occupied the entire volume of the mixture
